  "summary": "A participatory 2014 protest Seder built in solidarity with immigrant hunger strikers. It offers unusually clear table orientation, shared-reading instructions, ritual explanations, and a compact Exodus narrative, but its Obama-era policy claims and campaign tactics are historical advocacy and must not be silently presented as current or politically neutral.",
  "sourceAssessment": {
    "voice": "Direct, communal, bilingual-aware, activist, and facilitator-led, with an emphasis on story sharing, questions, symbolic objects, and public solidarity.",
    "bestUses": [
      "Beginner orientation and permission to take turns reading",
      "Participatory and interfaith table practices",
      "An accessible compact Exodus narrative",
      "Immigrant-justice Yachatz and protest-Seder history when explicitly selected"
    ],
    "beginnerRisks": [
      "The original event was a foodless public protest outside the White House, not a conventional home meal.",
      "Campaign claims, legal details, officials, and statistics describe 2014 and are not current guidance.",
      "Several modules quote or adapt other Haggadot and must preserve their source-presented credits.",
      "Some extracted segments end by opening the next activity, so only complete source-order sequences should be used."
    ],
    "politicalContext": "This is explicitly immigrant-justice advocacy from the Obama era. Selecting a social-justice or interfaith theme can justify ritual passages, but named administrations, agencies, boycotts, divestment campaigns, and legislative claims require a separate historical-activism opt-in. Its use of Mitzrayim deliberately avoids casting contemporary Egyptians or Arabs as villains and is compatible with the project's peace-focused policy.",
    "creditContext": "Credit Danielle Gershkoff, Rachel Lerman, Rachel Beck, Margot Seigle, Open Siddur, and Seder in the Streets Passover Haggadah on the final sources page. Preserve the named source for embedded JFREJ, JCA, Avodah, JOI, family-Haggadah, and other borrowed readings."
  },
